<dl id="n54077x"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54077x">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54077x"> 77(x)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ marie, marie, ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54077x"><li>FW 4.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54077x">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54077x">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54077x">MS BL 47476a-134</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:291 <a name="ad7" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad7.htm#n54077x">Draft: I.1&sect;1.7</a>/2.7</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Listen (said Brother Jan) to the oracle of the bells of Varene. What are they saying? I understand them (Panurge replied). Their sound is, <i>par ma soif</i>, more fateful than the cauldrons of Jupiter in the Dodone. Listen: Marie toy, marie toy, <mark><i>marie</i>, <i>marie</i></mark>. Si tu te marie, marie, marie, tres bien t&apos;en trouveras, veras, veras. Marie, marie&rdquo;. But Panurge listened afresh to the same bells and this time the message was quite different: &ldquo;Marie <i>poinct</i>, marie poinct, poinct, poinct, poinct, poinct, poinct.&rdquo; <small> L. Sainean, <a name="LSLR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LSLR"><cite title="source">La Langue de Rabelais</cite></a> (1922) I (Contes Populaires) 227</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
